'''Market moving information''' is a term used in [[stock market]] investing, defined as information that would cause any reasonable investor to make a buy or sell decision.<ref>{{Cite journal|ssrn = 2579510|title = Reasonable Investor(s)|last = |first = |date = 2015|journal = Boston University Law Review|doi = |pmid = |access-date = }}</ref>  It is also sometimes referred to as [[material information]].

When a public company insider fails to publicly disclose material, market moving information to everyone and only to certain parties, that is called [[selective disclosure]], an act that is prohibited by the SEC's [[Regulation FD]].

Many types of events can be considered market moving information.  A bad freeze in Florida can cause the price of orange juice to increase.  An expected drought in the Midwest might cause corn or soybean prices to rise on fears of poor crop outputs and limited supplies.

